{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_immokalee_ver01/data/sn95047334/00529042474/1958040301/0191.xml":{"full_text":"Weightlifters To\nVie In Marianna\nMarianna Weightlifting\nChampion Bill LeMarks will at\ntempt to surpass his own pre\nvious record breaking lifts at\nthe Florida School for Boys at\nMarianna. Saturday, April 5.\nTeams from three states are\nexpected at the school for the\nhigh school weightlifting cham\npionships of the Southeastern\nAssociation of the Amateur Ath\nletic Union. They will come from\nFlorida, Georgia, and Alabama.\nWeighing in will begin at 1 p. m.\nin the school gymnasium, and\ncompetition will get underway\nat 2 p. m.\nMain thrill of the contests ac\ncording to Ralph Walker, 11,\nchairman of the Amateur Athle\ntic Union weightlifting division,\nwill be LeMack\u2019s daring try. The\n122 pound student from Auburn\ndale Highschool set four new\nrecords in a meet at FSB on\nJanuary 25. In Eua Gallie on\nMarch 8 he broke all four of\nthese new records.\nWalker said he has heard from\nLeMacks and that the state\nchampion is in good condition\naiiu i.upes to break his own latest\nrecords and push his amazing\nJanuary performance ever fur\nther into the background.\nAn entry from The Florida\nScnool r or Boys at Marianna also\npromises to make a good show\ning.\n\u201cWe\u2019re hoping this will be\nJames Oakley\u2019s meet,\u201d said Wal\nker, who is a phychologist at\nFSB.\nOakley will weigh in at 160\npounds. At a weight of 152, Wal\nker said, he pressed 175 pounds\nin the last official meet. And\nhe has been improving steadily.\nThe weight lifting chairman\nwill have charge of the meet.\nJudges will be Rev. James Ful\nmer and \u2022Ed Hare of FSB and\nJim Harkins of Tallahassee. Stu\ndents at FSB will watch the\nmeet, which will be open to pub\nlic for a small admission charge.\nCUT IN GUARD BARRED\nA House Armed Services sub\ncommittee has unanimously re\njected a Defense Department\nplan to reduce Army National\nGuard and Army Reserve forces\nby 10 per cent.\nThe panel\u2019s decision was not\nfinal, but it could lead to the\ndefeat of Pentagon plans.\nPRINCESS IS ALL SET\nMonte Carlo, Monaco Prin\ncess Grace of Monaco, who hopes\nfor a male heir to the throne, is\nprepared for one or more. She\nhas three different layettes in\npreparation.\nOne is all white, a second is\nstraw yellow, and the third is a\npale green. The former Grace\nKelly of Hollywood is expecting\nher second child around March\n15. Her first child, Princess\nCaroline, is 13 months old.\nPetty honors appeal to petty\nminds.\n/hurrahW\nit\u2019s spring^/\nagain!\nGREAT TIME\nFOR A NEW KODAK CAMERA\nbrownie SiaAt\nCAMERA U\nReflex camera for color\nslides at a low, low price!\nlook through the big reflex-type\nfinder to see your picture in od\nvonce. Set the lever to indicate\ncolor or black-and-white. Then\njust touch the feather-action\nshutter release. Get gorgeous\nEktachrome color slides, Koda\ncolor snapshots, or black-and\nwhite pictures. A great value!\nCamera Flosholder\n$10.75 $3.75\nHeadquarters for\nGadsden County\nCameras Supplies\nMOVIE STILL\nEASTMAN BELL\nHOWELL\nAGENCIES\nCROUCH'S\nCorner Madison k Jefferson\n(YES!) you can buy\nKodak equipment |g\non time\nAfter signing a proclamation designating April as Cancer\nControl Month in Florida, Governor Le\u00dfoy Cpllins presents it\nto Dr. Harold D. Van Schaick, Chairman of the 1958 Cancer\nCrusade of the American Cancer Society. Goals of the Crusade\nare to bring true facts about cancer to the public through an\neducational program and to raise $650,000 to finance the over\nall program of research, education and service of the Florida\nDivision of the Society. Dr. Van Schaick holds the Sword of\nHope, emblem of the Society.\nNET STAR COURTS DEEP SEA-Mrs. Beverly Baker Fleitz, of\nLa Jolla, Calif., proves that a tennis star can double as an\nunderwater explorer. She is shown with her husband after\nscoring her sensational tennis upset by beating Althea Gibson,\nof New York, in the International Tennis Tourney at San Juan,\nPuerto Rico and then joining a skin-diving expedition.\nSEBRING, Fla. Gov. Le\u00dfoy Collins is Hie honorary starter for the\nFlorida international grand prix of endurance for sports cars Saturday,\nMarch 22, 10 a.m. to 10 p.m., at Sebring. The Governor gets in some\npractice with the checkered flag, with R. H. Burritt, Amoco division\nmanager, left, end Race Director Alec Ulmann, right.\nCostume jewelry being shown\nby leading designers to comple\nment the new dress creations has\ngone sophisticated and colorful.\nLiterally, it is flashing high,\nwide and handsome. It is found\nin the most unexpected places\n\u2014a pin at the nape of the neck,\nas a single adornment of a skirt,\nor leading a double life as a\nbarrette in the hair.\nThe emphasis on the chemise\nfor spring wear, with its simple.\nuncluttered lines is the perfect\nbackground for a woman to\nmake important use of colorful\ntouches of jewelry.\nOne of the most important\ntrends in jeweled accessories is\nthe payt color plays in the new\ncollections. Surprise color com\nbinations will be the order of\nthe day for spring and summer.\nSun colors are big fashion\nnews this spring, And are being\nused increasingly in earrings,\nnecklaces, brooches and rings.\nThese colors range from citron,\nthrough yellow, mango, orange,\npale greens to brilliant emeralds,\nand pale pinks or dubonnet reds.\nThe blues have taken on more\ninteresting shades than ever be\nfore, making full use of the\nclear Caribbean aquamarines\nthrough the deep midnight sap\nphire hues.\nNecklaces are more important\nthan ever in spring jewelry\nlines, and many designers are\nfavoring the longer look in dif\nferent types of necklaces and\nbibs. In the more expensive\nlines, a favorite is the \u201ccross\nover\u201d ascot in bright colors and\ntextures of costume jewels.\nPins are usually quite large\nand the trend toward shorter\nhair makes the wearing of ear\nrings a social must.\n\nSuccessful family life depends\nupon the teamwork of the mem\nbers of the family rather than\nupon individual joyrides.\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES. QUINCY\nBob Sixes Urges\nPrice Reductions\nTo Aid Business\nCongressman Bob Sikes in a\nspeech on the Floor of the House\nof Representatives recently said,\n\u201cMany proposals have been ad\nvanced as cures for recession.\nThe most important one has been\nmentioned but little and pushed\nnot at all. High Prices are our\nprincipal problem and the Pre\nsident could do no greater ser\nvice than to bring management\nand labor together in a determ\nined effort to reduce prices.\nOur economy is not in danger\nunless we talk recession into a\ndepression. Despite scare head\nlines in nearly every issue of the\nmajor publications, we are still\na prosperous Nation. A relati\nvely small percentage of our\npeople are unemployed. Savings\nare up. The Nation is sound and\nstrong.\nNow it is true that we have\nmore unemployed than we had\nlast year or that we have had\nin a good many years. But, also,\nwe have more people working\nthan in most of the years of our\nhistory. I believe the reasons for\nthe fact that unemployment has\ngrown in recent months are\neasily determined. People are\nSummer refreshment easy-care fashions...\ny\nI Kvl 11 T j illy t vJRI;-\n1 rWI\nMW\nHU Vt \u2022^4! l it? w\nJS&\nJowl\nAv Cw\nSix cool looks with A- f I I* vX Mt'\nthe accent on easy X f j d**\nI* ri i J x fe-\nliving ana easy-care fabrics.\nJ&J\nNelly Don interprets silhouette\nand color news in a refreshing 4 if J\ncollection of smart, young-looking 1^\ndesigns... each one finished with her\nfamous quality features. Ax\nA. Leaf print batiste in drip-dry, minimum- I\niron Dacron*. Green, brown, blue XWb 7 B\nor blade on white. 8 io 20. 1>.95\nB. Tucked-bodice coMoa chiffon f\nin a delicate sprig pant. Tebilized*\\ J J I\nfor crease resistance. Yellow, I\naqua, pink, lilac. Bto 18. 14.95 I\nC. Border-stripe dress in Dacron* ><V jF c/ 1 V|| I J \u2022^Sml I\nand cotton voile. Toast with black, Z I s I I\norange with brown, green with navy. B J f i\u00b0 I \\r\nBto 20 and custom sizes for the \u2019l I 1\u2022/ k V\nshorter figure, lOC to 20C. 17.95 vl* *4\nD. Jewel-button sheer in smart cartwheel\npint of little-iron Dacron* and cotton. i Vt IB V 111 1\nBlock, red, navy, brown. Bto 18. 17.95 [fl Iff r/B I\nE. The bon-bon dress with trapunto II ri /In I 11^\u2019 /A 1\nembroidery at the necUin.. f gHW .1 QI\nDacron* and cotton blend needs g \\\\U fl 7/ I rFBi I\nlittle ironing. Blue, pink, aqua, g fl mJPMkXI 1 1\nwhite, lilac. Bto 18. W.W tf'* l\\l II \u2022ft W \u00bbV \u201cA t\nF. Oetert poppy patio in drip-dry 1 I I i4l\ncotton satin that requires little ironing? t J I lI V J\nBlue, beige, green. Bto 18.14.95 0 j 1 I\nTH EJ. S. SHAW CO. U H W\nQUINCY FLA.\nFLORIDA. THURSDAY. APRIL 3. 1958\ntired of high pzict\u201e. Tnere has\nbeen a buyer\u2019s strike against\nprices that are lidiculously high\nfor products which stress gadget\nry more than service and reliabi\nlity. I believe, also, that people\nare apprehensive about the se\ncurity of our Nation, because\nthey are still disturbed by Rus\nsian progress in the scientific\nj field and in the diplomatic arena.\njOf course there are local ex\nceptions in areas where many\nof the unemployed formerly were\ngovernment workers. But in\nevery case this situation could\nfeed on itself and grow.\nThere are remedies and we\nneed to move promptly to take\nthe necessary steps. One major\nremedy is lower prices. The eco\nnomic experts agree that the\nfailure of prices to come down\nis the most unusual thing about\nthe current recession. That in\nitself is an admission this is no\nordinary recession generated by\neconomic weakness. People will\nstart buying again when there is\ngood reason for it. Certainly an\nattack on high prices is prefer\nable to hugh spending programs\nor to tax cuts.\nWe cannot spend ourselves in\nto prosperity through govern\nment appropriations. The mea\nsures which have been suggested,\nand they are many, are inreali\nty small-scale endeavors to re\nstore confidence by passing laws.\nA restoration of more general\nprosperity is much more certain\nif the President will take the\nlead in bringing about the nec\nessary action on the part of\nmanagement and labor to induce\nprice reductions. He has the\nprestige to insure proper co\noperation between management\nand labor and he has the power,\nif need be, to knock heads to\ngether to guarantee cooperation.\nThat doesn\u2019t mean merchants,\nmanufacturers and labor should\nwait. They can initiate action\nthemselves to show a restora\ntion of confidence in America.\nThe harder they work at it the\nmore quickly we will see a re\nsurgence of business activities\nthroughout the Nation and see\nan end to unemployment and re\ncession.\nASK UNIFICATION STEP\nPanmunjom, Korea North\nKorea has called for the with\ndrawal of the United Nations\nforces from South Korea as the\nfirst step toward unification of\nKorea.\nThe Communists also propos\ned a \u201cfree election\u201d throughout\nKorea, and economic and cul\ntural exchanges bewteen North\nand South. The Communists pro\nposals were made at a meeting\nof the Military Armistice Com\nmission.\nHard work has killed lots of\nfolks.\nMUSIC-MINDED POODLES\u2014 The \u201ckitten on the keys\u201d idea gives\nway to two music-minded black poodle puppies in Offenbach,\nGermany. One of the pups holds a sheet of music while the\nother \u201cdigs\u201d a hot number on the piano. (International)\nPAGE FIVE","height":"29160","width":"20580"}}
